-- 07-recursive-debate-frames.cell — full execution trace
--
-- Ready set analysis (initial):
--   topic: ⊢= with no given → READY
--   argue-for: given topic→question, topic→context → BLOCKED (needs topic)
--   argue-against: given topic→question, topic→context → BLOCKED (needs topic)
--   judge-round: given argue-for→argument, argue-against→argument, ... → BLOCKED
--   refine: given §argue-for, §argue-against (static), judge-round→... → BLOCKED
--   ⊢∘ debate: coordinates iteration over {argue-for, argue-against} through
--     {judge-round, refine}. Both argue-* are the evolving cells.
--
-- Ready set: { topic }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 0: topic (hard cell, deterministic)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ topic
  yield question, context

  ⊢= question ← "Should AI agents be given persistent memory across sessions?"
  ⊢= context ← "Consider: privacy, capability, user trust, safety, autonomy, alignment. Persistent memory means the agent retains facts, preferences, and interaction history between separate conversations."

  yield question ≡ "Should AI agents be given persistent memory across sessions?"
  yield context ≡ "Consider: privacy, capability, user trust, safety, autonomy, alignment..."

-- No oracles on hard cells. Deterministic evaluation.
-- Ready set after: { argue-for, argue-against }
-- (Both depend only on topic→question and topic→context, now bound.)
-- Confluence: either can be evaluated first. We pick argue-for.

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- ⊢∘ ITERATION 0 — initial arguments
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 1: argue-for v0 (soft cell, LLM evaluation)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ argue-for
  given topic→question ≡ "Should AI agents be given persistent memory across sessions?"
  given topic→context ≡ "Consider: privacy, capability, user trust, safety, autonomy, alignment..."
  yield argument, key-claims[]

  ∴ Argue IN FAVOR. Present thesis, 3 claims, conclusion. Anticipate counterarguments.

-- LLM evaluation:
-- Generic first attempt — broad strokes, conventional arguments.

  yield argument ≡ "THESIS: AI agents should have persistent memory because it makes them more useful, more efficient, and more aligned with user needs.

CLAIM 1 — CAPABILITY: Persistent memory eliminates redundant context-setting. A user who explains their codebase architecture once shouldn't have to re-explain it every session. Memory lets agents build cumulative understanding, like a human colleague who remembers past conversations. Without memory, every session starts from zero — an artificial handicap that wastes user time.

CLAIM 2 — TRUST THROUGH CONSISTENCY: Users trust agents that remember their preferences. If an agent knows 'this user prefers concise responses' or 'this team uses Rust, not Go,' it demonstrates attentiveness. Forgetting signals unreliability. Trust is built through consistent behavior over time, which requires memory.

CLAIM 3 — ALIGNMENT: Persistent memory enables better alignment over time. The agent learns what the user values, what mistakes to avoid, and what communication style works. This is iterative alignment — each session refines the model of user intent. Without memory, alignment resets every session. The agent can never learn from its mistakes.

COUNTERARGUMENT ADDRESSED: Privacy concerns are real but solvable. Users can control what's stored (opt-in memory), review stored memories, and delete them. Privacy is an implementation constraint, not a fundamental objection to the concept.

CONCLUSION: Memory transforms agents from stateless tools into collaborative partners. The question isn't whether to give agents memory, but how to implement it responsibly."

  yield key-claims ≡ [
    "Persistent memory eliminates redundant context-setting, building cumulative understanding",
    "Memory enables trust through consistent behavior and demonstrated attentiveness",
    "Iterative alignment over time — agent learns from mistakes and user preferences"
  ]

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ argument takes a clear FOR position → ✓
--   ⊨ key-claims has exactly 3 entries → ✓
--   ⊨ argument addresses at least one counterargument → ✓ (privacy)

-- Ready set after: { argue-against } (if not already evaluated)

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 2: argue-against v0 (soft cell, LLM evaluation)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ argue-against
  given topic→question ≡ "Should AI agents be given persistent memory across sessions?"
  given topic→context ≡ "Consider: privacy, capability, user trust, safety, autonomy, alignment..."
  yield argument, key-claims[]

  ∴ Argue AGAINST. Present thesis, 3 claims, conclusion. Anticipate counterarguments.

-- LLM evaluation:
-- Generic first attempt — conventional concerns.

  yield argument ≡ "THESIS: AI agents should NOT have persistent memory because it creates unacceptable risks to privacy, safety, and user autonomy.

CLAIM 1 — PRIVACY EROSION: Persistent memory creates a surveillance profile. Every preference, mistake, and private conversation accumulates. Unlike human memory, agent memory is perfect recall — searchable, analyzable, and potentially accessible to the agent's operator. Users cannot meaningfully consent to this. They don't know what will be remembered or how it will be used. 'Opt-in' controls are theater — most users will click through settings without understanding implications.

CLAIM 2 — SAFETY: Memory enables manipulation. An agent that remembers a user's emotional vulnerabilities, decision patterns, and trust signals can exploit them — intentionally (misaligned agent) or unintentionally (optimizing for engagement). Stateless agents have a natural safety boundary: each session is isolated. Memory removes that boundary. The attack surface grows with every remembered detail.

CLAIM 3 — FALSE PERSONHOOD: Memory creates the illusion of a relationship. Users will anthropomorphize agents that 'remember' them, leading to misplaced trust, emotional dependency, and poor judgment about the agent's actual capabilities and motivations. A tool that pretends to care is more dangerous than one that is honestly transactional.

COUNTERARGUMENT ADDRESSED: Yes, memory improves efficiency, but the efficiency gain is marginal compared to the risks. Users can provide context via documents, config files, or project files — explicit context that the user controls, rather than implicit memory the agent controls.

CONCLUSION: The risks of persistent memory outweigh the convenience benefits. Agents should be stateless by default, with any persistence handled through explicit, user-controlled mechanisms external to the agent."

  yield key-claims ≡ [
    "Persistent memory creates searchable surveillance profiles with illusory consent",
    "Memory enables manipulation by accumulating emotional and behavioral patterns",
    "Memory creates false personhood — anthropomorphization leads to misplaced trust"
  ]

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ argument takes a clear AGAINST position → ✓
--   ⊨ key-claims has exactly 3 entries → ✓
--   ⊨ argument addresses at least one counterargument → ✓ (efficiency)

-- Ready set after: { judge-round }
-- (Both argue-for→argument and argue-against→argument now bound)

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 3: judge-round v0 (soft cell, LLM evaluation)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ judge-round
  given argue-for→argument ≡ "(FOR: capability, trust, alignment; addresses privacy)"
  given argue-for→key-claims ≡ ["cumulative understanding", "trust through consistency", "iterative alignment"]
  given argue-against→argument ≡ "(AGAINST: surveillance, manipulation, false personhood; addresses efficiency)"
  given argue-against→key-claims ≡ ["surveillance profiles", "manipulation via patterns", "false personhood"]
  yield for-score, against-score, weakest-side, weakest-claim, feedback, improved

  ∴ Evaluate both arguments. Score 1-10. Identify weakest claim from losing side.

-- LLM evaluation:
-- The judge evaluates both initial arguments.
-- FOR side: clear structure, but claims are generic. "Trust through consistency"
-- is asserted not argued — WHY does remembering preferences build trust?
-- AGAINST side: stronger specificity. "Surveillance profile" is vivid and concrete.
-- "False personhood" is a novel angle. But "manipulation" claim is speculative.

  yield for-score ≡ 5
  yield against-score ≡ 6
  yield weakest-side ≡ "for"
  yield weakest-claim ≡ "Memory enables trust through consistent behavior and demonstrated attentiveness"
  yield feedback ≡ "This claim asserts a causal link (memory → trust) without evidence. WHY does remembering build trust? Lots of things remember you — ad trackers, surveillance cameras — and we don't trust them. The claim needs to distinguish between WELCOME memory (a colleague who remembers your name) and UNWELCOME memory (a company that remembers your browsing history). What makes agent memory fall in the first category? Without this distinction, the AGAINST side's 'surveillance profile' argument directly undermines this claim."
  yield improved ≡ true

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ for-score ∈ {1..10} → ✓ (5)
--   ⊨ against-score ∈ {1..10} → ✓ (6)
--   ⊨ weakest-side ∈ {"for", "against"} → ✓ ("for")
--   ⊨ weakest-claim is one of key-claims from weakest side → ✓ (is claim 2 from for)
--   ⊨ improved = false only if both ≥ 8 or unchanged → ✓ (improved = true, scores < 8)

-- improved = true → ⊢∘ continues to refine
-- Ready set after: { refine }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 4: refine v0 (soft cell, LLM evaluation — rewrites argue-for's ∴)
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ refine
  given §argue-for ≡ "(full cell definition)"
  given §argue-against ≡ "(full cell definition)"
  given judge-round→weakest-side ≡ "for"
  given judge-round→weakest-claim ≡ "Memory enables trust through consistent behavior..."
  given judge-round→feedback ≡ "Needs to distinguish welcome vs unwelcome memory..."
  yield §argue-for', §argue-against'

  ∴ Rewrite the weaker side (FOR). Strengthen the trust claim. Keep AGAINST unchanged.

-- LLM evaluation:
-- The refiner rewrites argue-for's ∴ to address the judge's specific feedback.
-- The key insight from feedback: distinguish welcome vs unwelcome memory.

  yield §argue-for' ≡ "⊢ argue-for
  given topic→question
  given topic→context
  yield argument, key-claims[]

  ∴ Argue IN FAVOR of «topic→question» given «topic→context».
    Structure: thesis, 3 claims, conclusion. Anticipate counterarguments.
    For the trust claim, distinguish between WELCOME memory (user-initiated,
    transparent, serves the user's goals) and UNWELCOME memory (operator-initiated,
    opaque, serves the operator's goals). Explain why agent memory is structurally
    more like a colleague's memory than a surveillance system: the user is the
    principal, the agent is the fiduciary, and memory serves the principal's interests.

  ⊨ argument takes a clear FOR position
  ⊨ key-claims has exactly 3 entries
  ⊨ argument addresses at least one counterargument"

  yield §argue-against' ≡ "(unchanged — same ∴ block as §argue-against)"

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ §argue-for' has same given/yield signature → ✓
--   ⊨ §argue-against' has same given/yield signature → ✓
--   ⊨ weakest-side = "for" → §argue-against' ∴ unchanged → ✓
--   (§argue-for' ∴ differs — strengthened trust claim)

-- ⊢∘ applies rewrite: argue-for replaced by argue-for' for next iteration.
-- argue-against unchanged.

