  given argue-for→argument ≡ "(v3: structural safeguards, corrections over patterns, non-negotiable capability)"
  given argue-for→key-claims ≡ ["non-negotiable capability", "structural safeguards", "corrections over patterns"]
  given argue-against→argument ≡ "(v2: info asymmetry, naive fiduciary, consent boundary)"
  given argue-against→key-claims ≡ ["info asymmetry", "naive fiduciary", "consent boundary"]
  yield for-score, against-score, weakest-side, weakest-claim, feedback, improved

  ∴ Evaluate both arguments. Score 1-10.

-- LLM evaluation:
-- FOR v3 directly addresses the naive fiduciary rebuttal with structural safeguards.
-- The "corrections over patterns" distinction addresses revealed vs reflective.
-- The "explicit context IS memory" rebuttal is strong.
-- AGAINST v2 is still strong on info asymmetry but hasn't responded to the safeguards.
-- Both arguments are now sophisticated and well-structured.

  yield for-score ≡ 8
  yield against-score ≡ 8
  yield weakest-side ≡ "against"
  yield weakest-claim ≡ "Fiduciary defense is naive — real fiduciaries exploit clients; designer incentives override stated intent"
  yield feedback ≡ "The FOR side's structural safeguards rebuttal (auditable, inspectable, editable memory) directly undermines this claim. The AGAINST side needs to explain why structural safeguards would fail in practice — regulatory capture, dark patterns, user fatigue with audit tools. But both arguments are now at a high level."
  yield improved ≡ false

